Business owners always ask me the secret to 5 star success and frankly, it's hard to sum up in words.
How do you explain to someone, "Be really great at what you do... like better than everyone else.
" Lucky for me, I can use Merchant as an example.
Here's a great story about a place that knew it needed to make some changes, listened to feedback and implemented what people were saying and made smart decisions to the menu that keep me coming back.
I went tonight with someone who said, "Merchant... really?
I was there a year ago and it was sort of a mess, but if you vouch for it, I'll try it.
" He loved his rigatoni, I loved the hangar steak (cooked perfectly this time around) and we were both uber pleased with our server Lauren who made incredibly strong drink recommendations.
It was awesome to hear her passionately describe two of her favorites, and we decided to get 'em both.
The Fire & Wine includes a fun table side presentation that I won't spoil, but suffice it to say if you enjoy warm winter drinks, you need to get this.
Lauren was also super willing to ask the kitchen if they'd swap in the patatas bravas with my steak instead of the mustard mashed taters which are a little too creamy for me.
They did, and let me tell ya... this needs to be a thing.
Medium steak seasoned perfectly atop crispy potatoes with a zippy little aioli... it's like a Spanish version of steak frites.
Super good.
And I really appreciated that they were willing to make the switch.
So, in conclusion, when people ask me how to rock that 5-star review, I'll simply link to this one.
And I'll happily return to Merchant with people that were once turned off by it as long as they continue to grow, evolve and kill it!
(Which they totally are.

Arrived to Merchant at around 7:30pm on Friday night and found the place to be quite full.
After checking-in with the hostess, we made our way to the bar, where as luck would have it, 2 seats opened-up.
The wait for a table was only going to be 20 minutes; bar seats trump any wait, so we pulled our names from the wait list.
A friendly bartender introduced himself, offered drink and food menus, and gave us a minute or two.
We browsed the cocktail menu and decided on an Old Fashioned and a tap from Lake Louie.
The bar area at Merchant is nice; heavy timber, wide and spacious with comfy seats, and a perfectly placed toe rail made for great dining/drinking spot.
The patrons around us were friendly and engaging; one of them offered us a bite of her roasted beet entree, and we obliged - that's how friendly/chill the place is.
After perusing the menu and once again not being able to decide on an entree, we opted to sample a few appetizers.
Based on a tip from one of our bar neighbors, we ordered the mussels.
We also ordered the roasted bone marrow and the local cheese plate.
The food arrived after a short wait, and we immediately dove into the mussels.
Divine.
Truly divine.
The wine sauce was amazing; the rustic bread that accompanied the mussels was hearty yet chewy - perfect for transporting that awesome broth from the bowl to my beak.
Neither of us had tried bone marrow before, but we both loved it.
The presentation was wonderful, and the parsley butter (with shallot) that was served on top of the marrow helped accent the meaty flavor.
Thick slabs of grilled Texas toast were served on the side; the marrow spread like butter on the toast and was so silky smooth and phenomenal.
The local cheese plate featured three cheeses, including my all-time fave, Dunbarton Blue.
Local honey and a nice cranberry compote rounded out the dish.
The check arrived and was more than reasonable, especially given the quality of what we sampled.
Service was excellent, and the bartenders did a great, great job of making really excellent suggestions to us.
Merchant = WIN  Food = 4.25 stars Service = 4.5 stars Value = 4 stars MISC = 4 stars  I could see this becoming a regular hangout...

